A string stores a series of characters using quotations. ('"`).

A template literal allows for variables to be included in a string whilst maintaining clear and readable code.

E.g. Without the use of template literals:

const jonas = "I'm " + firstName + ', a ' + (year - birthYear) + ' years old ' + job + '!';
console.log(jonas);

E.g. With template literals:

const jonasNew = `I'm ${firstName}, a ${year - birthYear} years old ${job}!`;
console.log(jonasNew);


The string must begin and end using backticks (`) if it is to use template literals. 
Template literals are added to the string using ${}.

Template literal strings do not need to use \n\ for multi-lined strings. Instead, a template literal just needs to use the return key.

E.g. console.log(`String
multiple
lines`);